er argues that the British Mandatory government supported religious education as a supposed antidote to nationalist passions at the precise moment when the administrative, pedagogic, and curricular transformation of religious schooling rendered it a vital tool for Zionist and Palestinian leaders. This study of their policies and practices illuminates the tensions, similarities, and differences among these diverse educational and political philosophies, revealing the lasting significance of these debates for thinking about religion and political identity in the modern Middle East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEducation and statezPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aEducationxPolitical aspectszPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aIslamic religious educationzPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aJewish religious educationzPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aReligious educationzPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 4aBritish colonialism. 4aIslamic education. 4aJewish education. 4aPalestine. 4aZionism. 4amass politics. 4anationalism. 4areligious education. 4asecularism. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360452040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503604520423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503604520.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles